{"title_page": "Ercole de' Roberti", "text_new": "[[File:Ercole de' Roberti 001.jpg|thumb|240px|Portrait of ''[[Giovanni II Bentivoglio]]'' (c. 1480). National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.]]\n[[File:Ercole de' Roberti 010.jpg|thumb|240px|''Piet\u00e0'' (c. 1495). Walker Art Gallery, Liverpool, UK.]]\n'''Ercole de' Roberti''' (c. 1451 \u2013 1496), also known as '''Ercole Ferrarese''' or '''Ercole da Ferrara''', was an Italian artist of the Early [[Renaissance]] and the [[School of Ferrara]].  He was profiled in  [[Vasari]]'s ''[[Le Vite delle pi\u00f9 eccellenti pittori, scultori, ed architettori]]''.\n__NOTOC__\nThe son of the doorkeeper at the Este castle, Ercole later held the position of court artist for the [[House of Este|Este]] family in [[Ferrara]].  According to Vasari:\n\n{{quote|text=Ercole had an extraordinary love of wine, and his frequent drunkenness did much to shorten his life, which he had enjoyed without any accident up to the age of forty, when he was smitten one day by apoplexy, which made an end of him in a short time.<ref name=\"Vasari, Vite, profile of Ercole\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.efn.org/~acd/vite/VasariErcole.html |title=Vasari, ''Vite'', profile of Ercole |access-date=2007-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222203132/http://efn.org/~acd/vite/VasariErcole.html |archive-date=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nPaintings by Ercole are rare.  His life was short and many of his works have been destroyed.\n\n==Works==\nBy 1473, Ercole had left Ferrara and was working in [[Bologna]] in the studio of [[Francesco del Cossa]]. According to Vasari, Ercole also apprenticed under [[Lorenzo Costa]] in Bologna, but this seems unlikely as he was Lorenzo's senior by several years.<ref name=\"Vasari, Vite, profile of Ercole\"/> Vasari was likely confusing him with Ercole da Bologna or [[Ercole Banci]]. \nErcole's first mature works are his contributions to the Griffoni Chapel for the [[San Petronio Basilica]] in [[Bologna]]: a predella depicting the ''[[Miracles of St Vincent Ferrer]]'' (c. 1473) (now in the [[Pinacoteca Vaticana|Pinacoteca of the Vatican]]),<ref>[http://mv.vatican.va/3_EN/pages/x-Schede/PINs/PINs_Sala05_04_022.html The miracles of St Vincent Ferrer at the Vatican]</ref> and lateral pilasters for the altarpiece commissioned from del Cossa.\n\nErcole de' Roberti is known to have collaborated in the frescoes of [[Palazzo Schifanoia]]. In 1480, Ercole created a large altarpiece with a ''[[Madonna and Child Enthroned with Saints (Ercole de' Roberti)|Madonna and Child Enthroned with Saints]]''  for Santa Maria in Porto in [[Ravenna]], which is now in the [[Pinacoteca di Brera]], [[Milan]]. Portraits of [[Giovanni II Bentivoglio]] and Ginevra Bentivoglio attributed to Ercole de' Roberti (c. 1480) are in the National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.\n\nErcole succeeded [[Cosm\u00e8 Tura]] as court painter to the [[House of Este|Este]] family in Ferrara around 1486.\nHis role apparently went far beyond making art: he accompanied Alfonso d'Este on a papal visit to Rome, served as wardrobe manager for Isabella d'Este's wedding in [[Mantua]], and may even have made salamis.<ref>[http://www.getty.edu/art/gettyguide/artMakerDetails?maker=3380 Biographical Information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070710065133/http://www.getty.edu/art/gettyguide/artMakerDetails?maker=3380 |date=2007-07-10 }} on Ercole de' Roberti, J. Paul Getty Museum, Los Angeles.</ref>\n\nA painting of ''Portia and Brutus'' (c. 1486\u201390), believed to be painted for [[Eleanor of Naples, Duchess of Ferrara|Eleonora of Aragon]], duchess of Ferrara, is in the Kimbell Art Museum, Fort Worth, Texas.<ref>[http://www.kimbellart.org/database/index.cfm?detail=yes&ID=AP%201986.05 Kimball Art Museum, Fort Worth, Texas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210133737/http://www.kimbellart.org/database/index.cfm?detail=yes&ID=AP%201986.05 |date=2007-02-10 }}.</ref>  Ercole's painting of ''Saint Jerome in the Wilderness'' from this period is in the collection of the [[J. Paul Getty Museum]], Los Angeles. The Getty presented the first monographic exhibition of Ercole's work in 1999.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jaff\u00e9|first=David |display-authors=etal |date=1999|title=Ercole De' Roberti The Renaissance in Ferrara|journal=The Burlington Magazine|volume=141 |issue=1153|pages=i\u2013xl|jstor=888299 }}</ref> At The [[Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum]] in Madrid there is a small panel from a ''cassone'' or wedding chest attributed to him. From around 1480 it narrates an episode of [[Ovid]]'s famous ''[[Metamorphoses]]'', ''The argonauts leaving Colchis''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museothyssen.org/en/collection/artists/roberti-ercole/argonauts-leaving-colchis|title=The Argonauts Leaving Colchis|website=Museo Nacional Thyssen-Bornemisza|language=en|access-date=24 april 2020}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.getty.edu/art/collection/artists/3323/ercole-de'roberti-italian-about-1450-1496/ The J. Paul Getty Museum: Ercole de' Roberti]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090222203132/http://efn.org/~acd/vite/VasariErcole.html Vasari, ''Vite'', profile of Ercole]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081122094217/http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/collections/13c-16c/pieta.aspx 'Pieta' at the Walker Art Gallery, Liverpool, UK]\n*[http://www.getty.edu/art/gettyguide/artObjectDetails?artobj=1066 Information on ''St. Jerome in the Wilderness''], J. Paul Getty Museum, Los Angeles.\n*[https://www.nga.gov/collection/artist-info.1833.html Ercole de' Roberti at the National Gallery of Art] \n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberti, Ercole de'}}\n[[Category:1450s births]]\n[[Category:1496 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ferrara]]\n[[Category:15th-century Italian painters]]\n[[Category:Italian male painters]]\n[[Category:Ferrarese painters]]\n[[Category:Italian Renaissance painters]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ercole de' Roberti 001.jpg|thumb|240px|Portrait of ''[[Giovanni II Bentivoglio]]'' (c. 1480). National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C.]]\n[[File:Ercole de' Roberti 010.jpg|thumb|240px|''Piet\u00e0'' (c. 1495). Walker Art Gallery, Liverpool, UK.]]\n'''Ercole de' Roberti''' (c. 1451 \u2013 1496), also known as '''Ercole Ferrarese''' or '''Ercole da Ferrara''', was an Italian artist of the Early [[Renaissance]] and the [[School of Ferrara]].  He was profiled in  [[Vasari]]'s ''[[Le Vite delle pi\u00f9 eccellenti pittori, scultori, ed architettori]]''.\n__NOTOC__\nThe son of the doorkeeper at the Este castle, Ercole later held the position of court artist for the [[House of Este|Este]] family in [[Ferrara]].  According to Vasari:\n\n{{quote|text=Ercole had an extraordinary love of wine, and his frequent drunkenness did much to shorten his life, which he had enjoyed without any accident up to the age of forty, when he was smitten one day by apoplexy, which made an end of him in a short time.<ref name=\"Vasari, Vite, profile of Ercole\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.efn.org/~acd/vite/VasariErcole.html |title=Vasari, ''Vite'', profile of Ercole |access-date=2007-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222203132/http://efn.org/~acd/vite/VasariErcole.html |archive-date=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nPaintings by Ercole are rare.  His life was short and many of his works have been destroyed.\n\n==Works==\nBy 1473, Ercole had left Ferrara and was working in [[Bologna]] in the studio of [[Francesco del Cossa]]. According to Vasari, Ercole also apprenticed under [[Lorenzo Costa]] in Bologna, but this seems unlikely as he was Lorenzo's senior by several years.<ref name=\"Vasari, Vite, profile of Ercole\"/> Vasari was likely confusing him with Ercole da Bologna or [[Ercole Banci]]. \nErcole's first mature works are his contributions to the Griffoni Chapel for the [[San Petronio Basilica]] in [[Bologna]]: a predella depicting the ''[[Miracles of St Vincent Ferrer]]